Introduction

The churn rate, also known as the rate of attrition, is the percentage of subscribers to a service who discontinue their subscriptions to that service within a given time period. For a company to expand its clientele, its growth rate, as measured by the number of new customers, must exceed its churn rate. The rate is generally expressed as a percentage. (https://www.investopedia.com)

The goal of this project is to improve skills in data analysis and R programming language, while trying to identify and understand customer churning trends in telecom company data set. Main guidelines:

  • Keep it simple.
  • Make it fun.

Data: https://www.kaggle.com/hkalsi/telecom-company-customer-churn

Code: https://github.com/km1414/Kaggle/tree/master/churn-prediction

Getting and cleaning data (2)

Read and join data

  • Only train set used.
  • Data documentation denotes missing values in data set: '', '?', 'MISSINGVAL', 'NA'
  • Different format: 3 files - wide, 1 file - long.

Inspect data

  • 5298 observations, 25 variables (21 - character variables, 4 - numeric variables).
  • 4 variable groups: demographics info (gender, education, etc.), account info (contact type, charges, etc.), service details (streaming tv, online security, etc.), churn.
  • Missing values:

Getting and cleaning data (3)

Solve NA values

  • TotalCharges - drop 10 observations (new users, didn't pay yet).
  • Contract type - drop 5 observations (couldn't fill, important variable).
  • Country - drop variable (same value over whole data set).
  • State - drop variable (same value over whole data set).
  • Education - set NA values to Other.
  • Gender - fill NA values with most frequent value (low significance variable).

Tidy other variables

  • Dates converted from character to date.
  • Service variables standartized to have Yes and No levels.

Feature engineering

Editing features

  • New variable - MonthsSinceEntry = (Date of data collection - Date of customer entry) / 30
  • New variable - PaymentLevel = Total charges paid / Months since entry / Base cahrge - 1
  • New variable - ServiceType = Phone or Internet or Phone and Internet.
  • New variable - AdditionalServices = Count of additional services ordered (from different columns).
  • Drop used date variables.
  • Drop observations with extreme outliers (probably errors).
  • Convert all character variables to factor.

Data preview after cleaning

  • 5278 observations, 23 variables (18 - factor variables, 5 - numeric variables).
  • No missing values.

Exploratory data analysis (1)

Bigest part of customers have month-to-month contract type and has opportunity to churn any time. Most popular service type - phone and internet, electronic billing is more popular than classic billing. Churn rate reaches quarter of customers.

Exploratory data analysis (2)

Base charges slightly differ between different contract types because of additional services selected. No important outliers found.

Exploratory data analysis (3)

Phone service type has highest variance, but all distributions look similar. Payment level outliers weren't removed (except extreme outliers), because it could be significant churn indicator.

Exploratory data analysis (4)

Month-to-month contract type has bigest part of customers and highest churn rate (41%). Two year contracts have lowest churn rate (3%), and one year contracts have 11% churn rate.

Exploratory data analysis (5)

Electronic billing method includes more customers and higher churn rate among electronic billing users is higher (32% vs. 15%).

Exploratory data analysis (6)

Churn rate is also different in customer groups by payment method. Bank transfer (automatic) users have 17% churn rate, Credit card (automatic) - 16% Electronic check - 44% (the bigest rate), Mailed check - 18%.

Exploratory data analysis (7)

Churn rate, compared between different service types, shows 22% rate in only internet users group, 7% in phone users group and 31% in phone and internet users group. This group alse has bigest number of customers.

Exploratory data analysis (8)

Customers could be clustered into groups by service plan base charges, but payment level doesn't show obviuos dependencies.

Exploratory data analysis (9)

Biggest churn rate in standart education categories is in Graduation and Highschool or below groups (26% and 39%). Small group Other has 57%, Masters - 15%, Professional Qalification - 17%. Biggest part of customers entered at the start of data collection.

Exploratory data analysis (10)

Customers group with highest churning rate are users, entered in last 2-3 years, also have 4 or less additional services. Customers with two year contracts usually are older, have more additional services and very low churn rate.

Exploratory data analysis (11)

Customer target group could be seen as a strong red line. They are Phone and internet users, have month-to-month contract type and use electronic billing.

Exploratory data analysis (12)

Identify high risk - target group

  • Contract type - Month-to-month
  • ServiceType - Phone and Internet
  • ElectronicBilling - Yes
  • Payment method - Electronic check
  • Months since entry - < 36
  • Base charges - > 250

More conditions could be added to make group smaller.

The task is to convert these customers from potential churners into users with long term contracts.

Modeling (1)

Preprocessing

  • Convert factor variables to one-hot encoded variables.
  • Split data into Train and Test sets (80/20).

Modeling

  • Scaling, PCA, 5 fold - cross validation, hyper-parameter tuning, metric - AUC (area under curve).
  • Algorithms:
    • Logistic regression (caret)
    • Decision trees (caret)
    • Random forest (caret)
    • Support Vector Machines with Linear Kernel (caret)
    • Support Vector Machines with Radial Basis Function Kernel (caret)
    • Support Vector Machines with Polynomial Kernel (caret)
    • k-Nearest Neighbors (caret)
    • Neural network

Modeling (2)

Neural network model

  • 2 hidden layers (256, 32)
  • Adam optimizer, learning rate - 0.00025
  • Dropout - 0.4
  • 500 training iterations

Modeling (3)

Most important metric is AUC (area under curve), because model with highest AUC value, shows best prediction results while changing probability threshold.

Conclusion

  • Depending on threshold, up to 80%-90 % potential churn cases could be identified.
  • Real data results could be slightly worse, because of overfit.
  • More data beats better algorithms.
  • More info about data collection methods could uncover some data leakages.

Things to try next:

  • More detailed feature selection (drop unusful, add new).
  • Unsupervised learning methods (clustering).
  • Churn predictions in different groups (service type, contract type, etc.).
  • Ensembling different models.
